column8: P1. Leave the policy settings as they are.
column9: P2. Political measures that focus on less regulation  (e.g., policies that promote free trade agreements by reducing food regulations)
column10: P3. Political measures that include moderate regulation toward sustainable food production (e.g., banning certain pesticides, providing incentives for organic farming).
column11: P4. Political measures that include radical regulation toward sustainable food production (e.g., banning all pesticides, banning the import of foods produced using unsustainable methods).
column12: P5. Political measures that create incentives for local producers to produce sustainable foods (e.g., subsidies or tax breaks for local farmers who produce organic products).
column13: P6. Political measures aimed at investing in research to develop sustainable agricultural techniques or materials.
